    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <insight>
        <p>
            When objects are arranged in rows that increase by a constant number, the pattern forms an arithmetic sequence.
        </p>
        <p>
            In a triangular arrangement, the number of elements in each row increases by <m>1</m>:
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> 1, 2, 3, 4, \dots\amp </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            The total number of elements is the sum of this arithmetic sequence:
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow>S_n = \amp \; 1 + 2 + 3 + \dots + n</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            This can be calculated efficiently using:
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> S_n = \amp \frac{n}{2}(1+n)</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            Where <m>1</m> is the first term (<m>a</m>), <m>n</m> is the last term (<m>a +(n-1)d </m>), and <m>d</m> is the common difference of the sequence.
        </p>
        <p>
            The general formula for the sum of the first <m>n</m> terms of an arithmetic sequence is:
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> S_n = \amp \frac{n}{2}(2a +(n-1)d)</mrow>
            </md>
            
        </p>
        <p>
            This pattern is known as a triangular number and appears in many real-life arrangements.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->
     <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Consider the following arithmatic sequence, <m>1,4,7,10, ...</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Find the sum os the first
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>10</m> terms.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>100</m> terms.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>a = 1, d = 3, \;\text{and}\; n = 10 </m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>\therefore s_n = \frac{n}{2}[2a + (n-1)d] </m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> s_{10} = \amp\; \frac{10}{2}[2\times 1 + (10-1)3] </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \; 5[2+27] </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \; 5\times 29 </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \; 145 </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>a = 1, d = 3, \;\text{and}\; n = 100 </m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>\therefore s_n = \frac{n}{2}[2a + (n-1)d] </m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> s_{100} = \amp\; \frac{100}{2}[2\times 1 + (100-1)3] </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \; 50[2+99 \times 3] </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \; 5\times 299 </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \; 14,950 </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
     </example>
     <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The sum of the first eight terms of an arithmatic progression (A.P.) is <m>220</m>. If the third term is <m>17</m>, find the sum of the first six terms.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> s_8 =  \amp\; \frac{8}{2}[2a + (8-1)d] </mrow>
                    <mrow> 220 = \amp \; 4(2a + 7d) </mrow> 
                    <mrow> 220 = \amp \; 8a + 28d .......(i) </mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                The third term is <m>a + (3-1) d = 17 </m>: <m>17 = a+2d .......(ii)</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Solving (i) and (ii) simultaneously
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> 17  =\amp \; a+2d </mrow>
                    <mrow> 220 = \amp \; 8a + 28d </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> 220 = \amp \; 8a + 28d </mrow>
                    <mrow> 136 = \amp \; 8a + 16d </mrow>
                    <mrow> \therefore 12d = \amp \; 84 </mrow>
                    <mrow> d = \amp \; 7 </mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                Substituting <m>d = 7</m> in equation (ii) gives <m>a = 3</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Therefore}\; s_6 =  \amp \; \frac{6}{2}[2 \times 3 + (6-1)7] </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \; 3(6 \times 35) </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \; 3 \times 41 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \; 123 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
     </example>

